renigd Koninkrijk","Corby, Northamptonshire, England":"Corby, Northamptonshire, England","Birch, Essex, England":"Birch, Essex, England"},"en":{"1525–1600":"1525–1600","1528–1550":"1528–1550","1542–1592":"1542–1592","1545–Female":"1545–Deceased","1500–1580":"1500–1580","1550":"1550","1571":"1571","1592":"1592","1580":"1580","1525":"1525","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1600":"1600","1545":"1545","1500":"1500","1587":"1587","1542":"1542","about 1545":"about 1545","January 1550":"January 1550","1585":"1585","after 1592":"after 1592","1528":"1528","1549":"1549","Hatfield, Nottinghamshire England":"Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","Southwell, Nottinghamshire, England":"Southwell, Nottinghamshire, England","England":"England, United Kingdom","Corby, Northamptonshire, England":"Corby, Northamptonshire, England","Birch, Essex, England":"Birch, Essex, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Neepe","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Naois</b> (see   McNeese  ).","North German: from a short form of the female personal name   Agnes  .","German: habitational name from Neese (Mecklenburg-West Pomerania)."],"variants":[{"name":"McNeese","meanings":["Scottish and Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Naois</b>, a patronymic from a short form of the personal name <i>Aonghus</i>, see   Angus  , after the loss of <i>gh</i> caused compensatory lengthening of the second syllable. Compare   McGinnis   and   McInnis  ."]},{"name":"Nacey","meanings":["Americanized form of German   Neese   2."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":24,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":33,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705205,"age":44,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705206,"age":46,"year":"1571","julianDay":2294856,"title":"The Royal Exchange is Organized","description":"The Royal Exchange was organized in January 1571 by Sir Thomas Gresham. Gresham is known as the father of English banking.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705207,"age":60,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England establishe